.TH "SCHEDULER.YIELD" "3JS" "July 28, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Scheduler.yield \- Scheduler: yield() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]Note:\f[R] This feature is available in Web Workers.
.PP
The \f[B]\f[CB]yield()\f[B]\f[R] method of the \f[CR]Scheduler\f[R]
interface is used for yielding to the main thread during a task and
continuing execution later, with the continuation scheduled as a
prioritized task (see the Prioritized Task Scheduling API for more
information).
This allows long\-running work to be broken up so the browser stays
responsive.
.PP
The task can continue when the promise returned by the method is
resolved.
The priority for when the promise is resolved defaults to
\f[CR]\(dquser\-visible\(dq\f[R], but can inherit a different priority
if the \f[CR]yield()\f[R] call occurs within a
\f[CR]Scheduler.postTask()\f[R] callback.
.PP
In addition, the continuation of work after the \f[CR]yield()\f[R] call
can be canceled if it occurs within a \f[CR]postTask()\f[R] callback and
the task is aborted.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
yield()
.EE
.SS Parameters
None.
.SS Return value
Returns a \f[CR]Promise\f[R] that is fulfilled with
\f[CR]undefined\f[R], or rejected with an \f[CR]AbortSignal.reason\f[R].
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Feature checking
Check whether prioritized task scheduling is supported by testing for
\f[CR]scheduler.yield\f[R] on \f[CR]globalThis\f[R], either in a window
or worker scope.
.PP
For example, the code below logs
\f[CR]\(dqscheduler.yield: Supported\(dq\f[R] if the API is supported in
the current browser.
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// Check for support before using.\f[R]
\f[B]if\f[R] (globalThis.scheduler?.yield) {
  console.log(\(dqscheduler.yield: Supported\(dq);
} \f[B]else\f[R] {
  console.error(\(dqscheduler.yield: NOT Supported\(dq);
}
.EE
.SS Basic usage
Long tasks can be broken up by awaiting \f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R].
The function returns a promise, yielding to the main thread to allow the
browser to execute other pending work\(emlike responding to user
input\(emif needed.
The browser schedules a follow\-up task that resolves the promise, at
which point execution of the code can continue where it left off.
.PP
For instance, if a \f[CR]click\f[R] event listener on a button results
in significant work to load and display new page content, there will be
no visual feedback to the user that their button click was even
registered by the page until that work is complete.
A \f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R] can be inserted into the event listener
so that quick feedback can be shown (like a spinner), and then the
remainder of the work can be done when execution continues after the
yield.
.IP
.EX
button.addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, \f[B]async\f[R] () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[I]// Provide immediate feedback so the user knows their click was received.\f[R]
  showSpinner();
  \f[B]await\f[R] scheduler.yield();
  \f[I]// Do longer processing\f[R]
  doSlowContentSwap();
});
.EE
.PP
It may also be sufficient to provide quick interaction feedback with the
default UI.
For instance, if a \f[CR]change\f[R] event listener on a checkbox
triggers slow filtering of page content, a \f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R]
call can be inserted to show the check state change immediately before
continuing to the remainder of the event response.
.IP
.EX
checkbox.addEventListener(\(dqchange\(dq, \f[B]async\f[R] () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[B]await\f[R] scheduler.yield();
  doSlowContentFiltering();
});
.EE
.PP
In situations where there is lengthy work that needs to be done on the
main thread that can be chunked into a series of tasks,
\f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R] can be called repeatedly to keep the page
responsive throughout.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]function\f[R] doWork(value) {
  console.log(\(gawork chunk ${value}\(ga);
}

\f[B]const\f[R] workList = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4];

\f[B]for\f[R] (\f[B]const\f[R] work \f[B]of\f[R] workList) {
  doWork(work);
  \f[B]await\f[R] scheduler.yield();
}
.EE
.SS Yield priority
The order in which the promise returned by \f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R]
is resolved relative to other tasks is based on an implicit task
priority.
.PP
By default, \f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R] is run with a
\f[CR]\(dquser\-visible\(dq\f[R] priority.
However, continuation after a \f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R] call has a
slightly different behavior than \f[CR]scheduler.postTask()\f[R] tasks
of the same \f[CR]priority\f[R].
.PP
\f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R] enqueues its task in a boosted task queue
compared to a \f[CR]scheduler.postTask()\f[R] of the same priority
level.
So, for instance, a \f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R] continuation with
\f[CR]\(dquser\-visible\(dq\f[R] priority will be prioritized after
\f[CR]scheduler.postTask()\f[R] tasks of the higher
\f[CR]\(dquser\-blocking\(dq\f[R] priority level, but before
\f[CR]scheduler.postTask()\f[R] tasks of the same
\f[CR]\(dquser\-visible\(dq\f[R] priority (in the spec, this is defined
by a task queue\(cqs \c
.UR https://wicg.github.io/scheduling-apis/#scheduler-task-queue-effective-priority
effective priority
.UE \c
).
.PP
This is sometimes described as \f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R] enqueuing
its task at the front of a priority level\(cqs queue, while
\f[CR]scheduler.postTask()\f[R] tasks go at the end.
This can be a useful mental model.
In situations with just a few tasks, this means that with the same
priority, the \f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R] continuation will come first,
allowing additional flexibility in how tasks can be scheduled.
For example:
.IP
.EX
scheduler.postTask(() \f[B]=>\f[R] console.log(\(dquser\-visible postTask\(dq));
scheduler.postTask(() \f[B]=>\f[R] console.log(\(dquser\-blocking postTask\(dq), {
  priority: \(dquser\-blocking\(dq,
});
\f[B]await\f[R] scheduler.yield();
console.log(\(dquser\-visible yield\(dq);
.EE
.PP
will log the following:
.IP
.EX
user\-blocking postTask
user\-visible yield
user\-visible postTask
.EE
.PP
However, in cases where there are multiple \f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R]
calls, the distinction that the \f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R]
continuation tasks go into a boosted\-priority \f[I]queue\f[R] becomes
important because a second \f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R] task won\(cqt be
run before one that\(cqs already in the queue.
.PP
If one function yields its work before a second function does, the first
function to yield will continue first.
For example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]async\f[R] \f[B]function\f[R] first() {
  console.log(\(dqstarting first function\(dq);
  \f[B]await\f[R] scheduler.yield();
  console.log(\(dqending first function\(dq);
}

\f[B]async\f[R] \f[B]function\f[R] second() {
  console.log(\(dqstarting second function\(dq);
  \f[B]await\f[R] scheduler.yield();
  console.log(\(dqending second function\(dq);
}

first();
second();
.EE
.PP
will log the following:
.IP
.EX
starting first function
starting second function
ending first function
ending second function
.EE
.SS Inheriting task priorities
A \f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R] call within a
\f[CR]scheduler.postTask()\f[R] task will inherit the task\(cqs
priority.
For example, work after a \f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R] within a
low\-priority \f[CR]\(dqbackground\(dq\f[R] task will also be scheduled
as \f[CR]\(dqbackground\(dq\f[R] by default (but, again, inserted in the
boosted \f[CR]\(dqbackground\(dq\f[R] priority queue so running before
any \f[CR]\(dqbackground\(dq\f[R] \f[CR]postTask()\f[R] tasks).
.PP
For example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]async\f[R] \f[B]function\f[R] backgroundWork() {
  scheduler.postTask(() \f[B]=>\f[R] console.log(\(dqbackground postTask\(dq), {
    priority: \(dqbackground\(dq,
  });
  scheduler.postTask(() \f[B]=>\f[R] console.log(\(dquser\-visible postTask\(dq), {
    priority: \(dquser\-visible\(dq,
  });
  \f[I]// yield() inherits \(dqbackground\(dq priority from surrounding task.\f[R]
  \f[B]await\f[R] scheduler.yield();
  console.log(\(dqdefault\-background yield\(dq);
}

\f[B]await\f[R] scheduler.postTask(backgroundWork, { priority: \(dqbackground\(dq });
.EE
.PP
will log the following:
.IP
.EX
user\-visible postTask
default\-background yield
background postTask
.EE
.PP
\f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R] continuations will inherit whatever
priority the containing \f[CR]scheduler.postTask()\f[R] task has,
including whether the task\(cqs priority was changed dynamically.
.SS Aborting a yield
Similar to setting priority, a \f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R] call
can\(cqt be aborted directly, but it will inherit the abort signal from
a surrounding \f[CR]scheduler.postTask()\f[R] task.
Aborting the task will also abort any pending yields within it.
.PP
This example uses a \f[CR]TaskController\f[R] to abort a task with a
\f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R] within it.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] taskController = \f[B]new\f[R] TaskController();

\f[B]function\f[R] firstHalfOfWork() {
  console.log(\(dqfirst half of work\(dq);
  taskController.abort(\(dqcancel work\(dq);
}

\f[B]function\f[R] secondHalfOfWork() {
  \f[I]// Never runs.\f[R]
  console.log(\(dqsecond half of work\(dq);
}

scheduler.postTask(
  \f[B]async\f[R] () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
    firstHalfOfWork();
    \f[B]await\f[R] scheduler.yield();
    secondHalfOfWork();
  },
  { signal: taskController.signal },
);
.EE
.PP
The example is somewhat contrived in that it always triggers the
\f[CR]taskController.abort()\f[R] call within the task itself, but the
\f[CR]abort()\f[R] call could come from anywhere.
For example, it could be triggered by the user pressing a `Cancel'
button.
.PP
In this case, the \f[CR]abort()\f[R] occurs after the
\f[CR]scheduler.postTask()\f[R] task has already started
(\f[CR]\(dqfirst half of work\(dq\f[R] is logged), but the yield call
inherits the abort signal therefore the
\f[CR]await scheduler.yield()\f[R] call will throw with an abort reason
of \f[CR]\(dqcancel work\(dq\f[R].
.SS Using \f[CR]yield()\f[R] within \f[CR]requestIdleCallback()\f[R]
\f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R] calls also inherit their priority from
\f[CR]Window.requestIdleCallback()\f[R], when called from inside the
callback function.
In this case, the \f[CR]\(dqbackground\(dq\f[R] priority value is
inherited.
Note however that \f[CR]scheduler.yield()\f[R] calls inside
\f[CR]requestIdleCallback()\f[R] callbacks are not abortable.
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
Prioritized Task Scheduling API
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Scheduler\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Scheduler.postTask()\f[R]
